! CodeMirror 6 Editor for TiddlyWiki - Overview

Welcome! This guide explains everything about the CodeMirror 6 Editor plugin in simple terms. Think of it as a super-powered text editor that makes writing in TiddlyWiki way more fun and easier.

!! What is this plugin?

You know how when you write code or notes, it's nice when things are colorful and organized? That's what this plugin does! It replaces TiddlyWiki's basic text editor with a fancy one called "CodeMirror 6" that has tons of cool features.

---

!! The Main Editor

!!! CodeMirror 6 Editor (The Core)

This is the main plugin that everything else builds on. It gives you:

* ''Syntax Highlighting'' - Different parts of your text get different colors, making it easier to read
* ''Auto-completion'' - Start typing and it suggests what you might want to write (like autocomplete on your phone!)
* ''Bracket Matching'' - When you click on a bracket `(` or `[`, it shows you where the matching one is
* ''Auto-close Brackets'' - Type `(` and it automatically adds `)` for you
* ''Multiple Cursors'' - Hold Ctrl and click to type in multiple places at once (super cool!)
* ''Undo/Redo'' - Made a mistake? Ctrl+Z to undo, Ctrl+Y to redo
* ''Search & Replace'' - Find text and replace it with something else

---

!! Language Plugins

These plugins teach the editor how to understand and colorize different programming languages. When you write code blocks, the editor will highlight the code beautifully!

!!! TiddlyWiki Mode
The most important one! It understands TiddlyWiki's special syntax:
* WikiLinks like `[[My Page]]`
* Bold `''text''` and italic `//text//`
* Headings, lists, tables
* Widgets like `<$list>` and `<$button>`
* Macros like `<<myMacro>>`
* Filters like `[tag[example]]`
* Typed blocks with syntax highlighting (`$$$.js`, `$$$.css`, etc.)

!!! Other Languages
* ''CSS'' - For styling (colors, fonts, layouts)
* ''HTML'' - For web page structure
* ''JavaScript'' - The programming language of the web
* ''JSON'' - For data (like settings files)
* ''Markdown'' - Another way to format text
* ''Python'' - A popular programming language
* ''SQL'' - For database queries
* ''XML'' - For structured data
* ''YAML'' - For configuration files

